  "opinion": "As a plumber in Lecce with only a lower secondary education, I've seen how stereotypes about STEM fields can really affect people. Stereotype threat is when someone feels stressed because they think they might confirm a negative stereotype about their group. For example, if a girl thinks she's not good at math because she's a girl, she might avoid solving problems, which makes her perform worse. This isn't just a problem for girls; it affects people from all backgrounds. In my job, I've noticed that when someone is nervous about being judged for their skills, they don't do as well as they could. I think we should address this by creating environments where everyone feels safe to try and make mistakes. Schools and workplaces should have programs that show how diverse people can excel in STEM, not just focus on the 'right' answers. It's important to have role models who look like you, because seeing someone from your background succeed can boost confidence. I don't have social media, so I don't see a lot of online discussions, but I've talked to people in my community about this. They agree that when you feel safe, you can do better. In Lecce, where we have strong family ties and community support, it's easier to build trust and encourage people to pursue their interests without fear. I believe addressing stereotype threat starts with simple steps like listening to people's experiences and making sure everyone knows their worth, regardless of their background.",
